Release fires on both success and failure — Effect.scoped closes the Scope carrying the finalisers.

Effect.acquireRelease returns an `Effect<A, E, Scope>` — the `Scope` in the requirement channel tells the type system "this effect needs a scope to pin the finaliser to." Until you wrap the program with `Effect.scoped`, that Scope stays in R. `Effect.scoped` provides a fresh scope, runs the program, and closes the scope (running all registered finalisers in reverse order) regardless of success or failure.

